  "topic_id": "T06.01",
  "topic_name": "Types of Chemical Reactions",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Chemical reactions are classified based on how reactants combine to form products. Combination reactions: two or more substances combine to form one product (A + B → AB). Decomposition reactions: one compound breaks down into simpler substances (AB → A + B). Decomposition can be thermal, electrolytic, or photolytic. Displacement reactions: a more reactive element replaces a less reactive one. The reactivity series helps predict displacement reactions. Double displacement reactions: two compounds exchange ions. Neutralization is acid + base → salt + water. Exothermic reactions release heat; endothermic reactions absorb heat.",
    "rules": [
      "Combination: A + B → AB (synthesis)",
      "Decomposition: AB → A + B (analysis)",
      "Types of decomposition: thermal, electrolytic, photolytic",
      "Displacement: more reactive element replaces less reactive",
      "Reactivity series: K, Na, Ca, Mg, Al, Zn, Fe, Pb, H, Cu, Ag, Au",
      "Double displacement: exchange of ions between compounds",
      "Neutralization: Acid + Base → Salt + Water",
      "Exothermic: releases heat (ΔH negative)",
      "Endothermic: absorbs heat (ΔH positive)"
    ]
  },
